# MEMBER 1 — Synchronization (Reader-Writer + Critical Section)

---

## What to Say to Mam

> "In an OS, multiple processes may access shared memory simultaneously.
> Without synchronization, two threads writing at the same time corrupt data.
>
> Our project implements the **Reader-Writer Problem**:
> Multiple users can CHECK balance at the same time (shared read).
> But only ONE user can DEPOSIT or WITHDRAW at a time (exclusive write).
>
> We use Java's ReentrantReadWriteLock — one lock per bank account.
> Each account is a **critical section** — code that only one thread enters at a time.
> This matches exactly what OS theory defines as the critical section problem."

---

## Code to Show

**File: `src/kernel/ReadWriteManager.java`**
```java
// One lock per account = one lock per shared resource
private ConcurrentHashMap<String, ReentrantReadWriteLock> locks
    = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

public ReentrantReadWriteLock getLock(String accountName) {
    locks.putIfAbsent(accountName, new ReentrantReadWriteLock());
    return locks.get(accountName);
}
```

**File: `src/system/BankDatabase.java` — Read Lock (balance)**
```java
// READER: multiple threads can read balance simultaneously
lock.readLock().lock();
try {
    System.out.println("Balance = " + acc.getBalance()); // shared access OK
} finally {
    lock.readLock().unlock();
}
```

**File: `src/system/BankDatabase.java` — Write Lock (deposit/withdraw)**
```java
// WRITER: only ONE thread can deposit at a time (critical section)
lock.writeLock().lock();
try {
    account.deposit(amount);       // exclusive access
    persistAccount(account);
} finally {
    lock.writeLock().unlock();
}
```

**Explain the two rules:**
```
Read Lock  → multiple threads can hold simultaneously (shared)
Write Lock → only ONE thread holds, all others WAIT (exclusive = critical section)

This solves:
  Mutual Exclusion  (only one writer at a time) ✅
  Progress          (lock is always released)   ✅
  Bounded Waiting   (Java's fair lock option)   ✅
```

