# MEMBER 2 — Scheduling (Round Robin + Priority)

---

## What to Say to Mam

> "An OS scheduler decides WHICH process runs NEXT and for HOW LONG.
>
> Our project implements TWO scheduling algorithms simultaneously:
>
> Round Robin: Each transaction gets a fixed time slice (quantum = 3 units).
> After its time is up, it goes back to the queue. Fair for all.
>
> Priority Scheduling: High priority transactions (transfers) run before
> low priority ones (balance checks). If a high priority job arrives,
> it runs next regardless of queue order.
>
> Every banking operation (deposit, withdraw, transfer) becomes a
> TransactionProcess — with a process ID, priority, and task.
> The scheduler manages these exactly like an OS manages PCBs."

---

## Code to Show

**File: `src/kernel/scheduler/TransactionProcess.java`**
```java
// Each operation becomes a process (like PCB in OS)
public class TransactionProcess {
    private String processId;    // unique process ID
    private Runnable task;       // what the process does
    private int priority;        // higher = runs first
    private int timeSlice = 3;   // quantum for round robin
}
```

**File: `src/kernel/scheduler/RoundRobinQueue.java`**
```java
// FIFO queue = Round Robin base
private Queue<TransactionProcess> queue = new LinkedList<>();

public void addProcess(TransactionProcess p) {
    queue.add(p);       // add to tail
}
public TransactionProcess getNext() {
    return queue.poll(); // remove from head = FIFO order
}
```

**File: `src/kernel/scheduler/PriorityScheduler.java`**
```java
// Priority queue — higher priority runs first
private PriorityBlockingQueue<TransactionProcess> priorityQueue
    = new PriorityBlockingQueue<>(10,
        (a, b) -> b.getPriority() - a.getPriority()); // higher number = first
```

**File: `src/kernel/TransactionManager.java` — Priority assignment**
```java
// Transfer = priority 1 (high — involves two accounts)
new TransactionProcess("TX-"+id, task, 1);

// Create account = priority 2 (highest — setup operation)
new TransactionProcess("TX-"+id, task, 2);
```

**Explain:**
```
Round Robin  → fair execution, each process gets equal quantum
Priority     → urgent operations (transfer) before routine ones
Together     → same as Multi-Level Queue scheduling in OS theory
```

