# MEMBER 4 — Deadlock Avoidance (Banker's Algorithm)

---

## What to Say to Mam

> "Deadlock Prevention eliminates a condition by design.
> Deadlock Avoidance is smarter — it allows more flexibility but
> checks at RUNTIME whether granting a resource request is safe.
>
> We implemented Banker's Algorithm — named after banking systems
> where a bank must keep enough reserve to serve all customers.
>
> In our project:
>   Resource = bank account (each account is a resource to be locked)
>   Process  = transfer transaction (needs 2 accounts: sender + receiver)
>
> Before EVERY transfer, Banker's Algorithm runs a Safety Algorithm:
>   Step 1: Pretend to grant the requested accounts
>   Step 2: Check if ALL pending processes can still complete
>   Step 3: If YES (safe sequence found) → allow transfer
>            If NO (unsafe state) → block transfer
>
> This is deadlock AVOIDANCE — we never enter an unsafe state."

---

## Code to Show

**File: `src/kernel/BankersAlgorithm.java` — Safety Algorithm**
```java
public synchronized boolean requestAndCheck(String processId, Set<String> needed) {

    // Step 1: Calculate available resources
    Set<String> available = all resources - currently allocated;

    // Step 2: Tentatively allocate to requesting process
    tempAlloc.put(processId, needed);
    tempAvailable.removeAll(needed);

    // Step 3: Safety Algorithm
    while (progress) {
        for each process:
            need = max - allocation          // what it still needs
            if (available >= need):          // can it finish?
                available += allocation      // release its resources
                add to safe sequence
                progress = true
    }

    // Step 4: Decision
    if (all processes in safe sequence):
        return true;   // SAFE → allow transfer
    else:
        return false;  // UNSAFE → block transfer
}
```

**File: `src/kernel/TransactionManager.java` — Integration**
```java
private void submitTransfer(String from, String to, double amount) {

    Set<String> needed = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(from, to));

    // Banker's check BEFORE transfer executes
    if (!bankersAlgorithm.requestAndCheck(processId, needed)) {
        System.out.println("Transfer blocked — unsafe state.");
        return; // do not proceed
    }

    // Execute transfer only if safe
    submitKernelProcess(process);

    // Release resources after completion
    bankersAlgorithm.release(processId);
}
```

