# Common Viva Questions + Answers

**Q: Is this a real OS or simulation?**
A: "It is a software-level OS simulation built in Java. JVM manages actual hardware. We implement OS algorithms and concepts at the application layer — standard for university OS projects."

**Q: What is the difference between prevention and avoidance?**
A: "Prevention eliminates a deadlock condition by design (lock ordering removes circular wait — no runtime cost). Avoidance checks safety at runtime before every resource grant (Banker's algorithm — can block requests)."

**Q: Why LRU and not FIFO?**
A: "LRU evicts the account used LEAST RECENTLY — if you just accessed alice, she likely needs to be accessed again soon. FIFO ignores usage pattern and evicts whoever arrived first regardless. LRU gives better hit rate for banking workloads."

**Q: What is the safe sequence in Banker's?**
A: "The safe sequence is the order in which all active processes can complete without deadlock. If no such sequence exists, the system is in unsafe state and we block the request."

**Q: What is a page fault here?**
A: "When an account is accessed but not in the LRU cache (frames), it is a page fault. The system reads the account from CSV (disk) and loads it into a frame — exactly like OS loading a page from swap into RAM."
